                                                                                   **Chapter   1**  
                                            **Design of ERDD**

ERDD system is designed such that on detection of tether breakage, a signal is sent to the main circuit, and then the flow of LTA gas through the valve is controlled. As soon as the valve is opened, LTA gas contained in the envelope starts to escape at a desired rate and after some time aerostat starts coming to ground.  ERDD circuit mainly consists of three subsystems, Tension detection, processing system, and valve actuation. The last stage is the ejection system, for reducing the impact velocity of the whole system so that the aerostat gradually descends to the ground. The operation of these mechanisms is described in detail in the following subsections.

**1.1   Tension detection**   
A spring-mass balance mechanism is used along with electrical components to detect loss of tension in the tether. The upper end of the spring balance will be attached to the confluence lines, and on the lower end, the tether will be attached. Electrical nodes are attached to the spring balance, as shown in figure 1, and the other node is fixed to the extreme end of the spring balance. Initially due to tension in tether the spring is elongated, and when the tether breaks, there is a loss of tension occurs and spring gets restored, results in the connection of electrical nodes. Completion of circuit ensures the signal is sent to the processing system. 

![][image3]![][image4]  
                                             Figure 1: Tension detection through spring balance mechanism  
       ![][image5]  Figure 2: Circuit Diagram of spring-mass system

**1.2  Processing System**  
As loss of tension is detected, a signal is sent to the Arduino UNO board. Then Arduino UNO process that the tether is broken and continues to execute ERDD. ERDD will be executed till the height becomes zero. As shown in the figure 3, the battery is powering the Arduino UNO. UNO then powers two servo motors and a receiver. ERDD can also be activated when given a signal using the transmitter. When the Arduino is activated, it controls the valve based on sensors inputs as well as manual transmitter inputs and releases gas according to the requirement. When descending, if the speed of aerostat exceeds than the desired (terminal) speed, the Arduino sends a signal to the Ballast release system to release in order to decrease the speed of the aerostat. For measuring the speed and height, we will have sensor which will give input to the Arduino.

 **1.3   Valve actuation**  
The valve is used to control the amount of LTA gas inside the envelope, which affects the buoyancy of the aerostat. The valve is typically located at the top of the envelope and is connected to a control system that regulates the gas pressure and volume. The valve can be actuated using two methods:

**Remote control:** This involves a transmitter and receiver opening or closing the valve to release LTA gas as needed.

**Autonomous control:** Automatic valve actuation is a method of controlling the amount of LTA gas inside an aerostat envelope, which affects the buoyancy of the aerostat. This method involves using sensors and control systems to automatically open or close the valve based on altitude and speed as determined by the algorithm and operational requirements.

The automatic valve actuation system operates by constantly monitoring the environment and making adjustments to the valve opening as needed to maintain a stable altitude and speed. For example, if the aerostat starts to rise due to a decrease in weight, the control system can open the valve to release some of the lifting gas and reduce the buoyancy of the aerostat. Similarly, if the aerostat starts to descend due to weight, the control system can close the valve to retain more of the lifting gas and maintain the buoyancy of the aerostat.

                 ** ![][image8]   ![][image9]**  
                                              Figure 5: Valve parts                                             Figure 6: Valve with servo motor

The valve we have used for ERDD consists of two discs, one of them is fixed, and the other one is rotated with the help of servo motor. Two annular discs are used for attachment of the valve with the envelope, one below envelope material and one above envelope material; these two discs and valve are joined with screws. To prevent leakage, one rubber ring is also added between the envelope material and the topmost disc.

**1.4   Ejection system or ballast release system**          
The ejection system allows us to release some of the components of the ERDD system and ballast during the process of deflation when needed. The hook will be attached along with a servo motor for hanging the ballast and spring-mass system. In descend phase, at some point, on the basis of altitude and speed feedback data, the Arduino will be coded such that the system calls the servo motor to rotate, causing the hook to rotate by an angle of 180 degrees or so, which allows the spring balance and ballast to get released from the system. This will help in order to maintain certain buoyancy and to generate a quick negative impulsive force to the Aerostat system. At the point of activation the terminal speed must have been reached and the height at which it will activate will be fixed after some calculations, trials and data from sensors. 

Another plan for ballast release is to make a structure similar to the valve but with multiple holes in the plates such that on rotation by a servo motor, anything kept on the disc (like ballast) will fall down through the holes.

            **2.3 Rate of Deflation (R)**  
The rate of deflation is a critical parameter to determine in order to achieve our targets. It can be measured as Volume flow rate (L^3T^-1). This parameter is more or less the only thing that can be controlled by us in the process of creating the best ERDD system, and it helps us to get a good relation between the total time and speed of impact of our system.   
In order to achieve the best with the system, determining the value of R at different times is very important.   
![][image11]  
**Figure 8 Trajectory of Aerostat**

The whole path of the system is divided by us into four parts, and the values of R vary for different parts of the process as follows:-

| Phase  | Description | Expected Working |
| :---- | ----- | ----- |
|   | Ascent Phase |  |
| A | Till system attains neutral buoyancy (Buoyancy force equals Weight of the system, after cutting the tether)  | The Rate of deflation should be the maximum possible till stage B to deflate the envelope as soon as possible, which is our **major task** after the tether is cut. |
| B | Till system achieves zero vertically upward speed  |  |
|  | Descent Phase |  |
|  C | Till the vertical downward speed becomes the max allowed speed at impact.  | After that, the rate of deflation should be reduced such that phase C will occur before phase D. |
| D | Till the system actually hits the ground.  | The distance covered by our system in phase D will be going to be with no further loss of helium, i.e. R=0. And its speed should remain nearly constant.(Terminal speed).   |

        

           **Conclusion:**

1. In phases A and B valve will be fully opened.

2. for Phase C and D, valve opening percentage will be determined after complete physical testing of the system with sensors.

3. Somewhere at the phase D (where terminal speed is attained), using hit and trial testing and heigth sensor datas, the ejection system is activated to reduce the net buoyancy and thus speed of the system.

**Chapter   4**  
**Future scope of work**

 **4.1 Fabrication of envelope**    
The envelope would be a non-rigid spherical structure filled with Helium gas. It will be around 1.5   cubic meters in volume and will be sealed by joining together either 4 or 5 petals. A space for the valve will be created at the top surface of the envelope, which will be sealed along with the surface of the valve. Confluence lines will be added for tethering and attachment of gondola.

**4.2 Ejection system**       
Ejection system’s ideation is done. In descend phase, at some point, on the basis of altitude and speed, the Arduino will be coded such that the system calls the servo motor to rotate, and ballast will be released . Testing and building is yet to be done. 

**4.3 Adding sensors for environmental inputs**  
We will add sensors to measure altitude and speed of aerostat. One more sensor for measuring the pressure difference and flow rate over the valve. This will be input for the Arduino and based on this input control of servo motor and opening of valve will be decided. Exact sensors details to be decided at the time of testing.

**4.4 Physical testing of the entire system and trials**

Once the leakproof envelope is made and the valve is attached to it without any leakage through attachments, we will attach the ERDD system to envelope and test it with helium gas. More hit and trial method will be used to further optimise the time taken to complete the whole process.
